<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>sgCheckup - By Gold Fig Labs</title>
    <style>
      .report {

        display: flex;
        flex-direction: column;
        align-items: center;
      }

      .report table {
        font-size: 12px;
        border-spacing: 0;
        margin: auto;
      }

      .report td,
      .report th {
        border: 1px solid #888;
        padding: 4px 16px;
        text-align: center;
      }

      .report th {
        font-style: italic;
        font-weight: bold;
      }

      .red {
        background-color: #f4cccc;
      }

      .green {
        background-color: #d9ead3;
      }

      .yellow {
        background-color: #fff2cc;
      }

      .report td.identifier {
        text-align: left;
      }

      .two_columns {
        display: flex;
        flex-direction: row;
        justify-content: space-around;
        max-width: 900px;
        width: 100%;
      }

      .legend h3,
      .legend h4 {
        margin-bottom: 4px;
      }

      .two_columns section {
        padding-left: 8px;
        padding-right: 8px;
        padding-top: 0px;
        max-width: 50%;
      }

      .metadata {
        font-weight: bold;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <main class="report">
      <h1>sgCheckup - By Gold Fig Labs</h1>
      <div class="two_columns" style="width: 100%;">
        <section>
          <p>
            Security Groups snapshotted at:
            <span class="metadata">{{humanize .Report.Metadata.Imported}}</span>
          </p>
          <p>
            Report generated at:
            <span class="metadata">{{humanize .Report.Metadata.Generated}}</span>
          </p>
        </section>
        <section>
          <p>
            Organization:
            <span class="metadata">{{.Report.Metadata.Organization}}</span>
          </p>
          <p>Account ID: <span class="metadata">{{.Report.Metadata.Account}}</span></p>
        </section>
      </div>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>#</th>
            <th>ARN</th>
            <th>Name</th>
            <th>Status</th>
            <th>In&nbsp;Use</th>
            <th>Is&nbsp;Default</th>
            <th>Public IPs</th>
            <th>Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{range $index, $row := .Report.Rows}}
          <tr>
            <td>{{inc $index}}</td>
            <td class="identifier">{{$row.Arn}}</td>
            <td class="identifier">{{$row.Name}}</td>
            <td class="{{$row.Status}}">{{$row.Status}}</td>
            <td>{{yn $row.InUse}}</td>
            <td>{{$row.IsDefault}}</td>
            <td>{{ipList $row.PublicIps}}</td>
            <td>{{notes $row.Notes}}</td>
          </tr>
          {{end}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <div class="legend">
        <h3>Legend</h3>
        <div class="two_columns">
          <section>
            <h4>Colors</h4>
            <p>
              <span class="red">Red</span> - This security group has ports open and contains instances with public IP
              addresses. Those instances can accept traffic on those ports, and it should be
              verified that this is intended.
            </p>
            <p>
              <span class="yellow">Yellow</span> - This security
              group is not ideal, but does not present an immediate risk. It is
              worth examining to see if it can be further locked down or removed,
              if unused.
            </p>
            <p>
              <span class="green">Green</span> - No recommendations
              for this security group.
            </p>
          </section>
          <section>
            <h4>Assumptions</h4>
            <p>
              Default security groups should not be used, and should be locked down.
              This prevents instances from accidentally inheriting open ports when
              created.
            </p>
            <p>
              Unused security groups should be removed, as they represent surface area
              that doesn't need to exist.
            </p>
            <p>
              Ports 22, 80, and 443 are assumed to be open intentionally. More mature
              organizations may wish to use an SSH bastion host and not open port 22 on
              every instance, or may with to disable all HTTP traffic, but for this report
              those changes are out-of-scope.
            </p>
            <p>
              While we do list IP addresses alongside ports that are open, we do not
              verify whether any of the instances are actually listening on those ports.
              However, we recommend not relying only on instances not actively listening
              on a port. The principle of defense-in-depth suggests that if an instance
              does not need a port open, the firewall should also enforce that.
            </p>
          </section>
        </div>
      </div>
    </main>
  </body>
</html>